            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "Daniel Kim is a product of San Francisco\u2019s fog and faded avenues. Born and raised in the Richmond District to first-generation Korean immigrants, his childhood was steeped in the quiet ambition of his parents. They ran a small dry-cleaning business on Geary Boulevard, and their dreams for Daniel were large\u2014a world of university degrees and professional prestige they\u2019d never had. Daniel, bright but more practical than academic, felt the weight of these expectations through high school.\n\nHis life\u2019s trajectory shifted abruptly at eighteen. Just as his friends were leaving for college, his mother was diagnosed with a debilitating long-term illness. University was no longer an option; his father needed him at the shop and his mother needed a caregiver. The decision felt less like a choice and more like a quiet pact of responsibility. For years, his world shrank to the blocks between his family's apartment and the dry cleaners, his life dictated by medication schedules and customer pickups.\n\nAfter his mother passed away when he was 24, the shop felt haunted by her absence. Seeking stability and a path of his own, Daniel took the civil service exam and joined the USPS. Becoming a mail carrier wasn\u2019t his parents\u2019 dream, but it offered union security and a pension\u2014a blue-collar bedrock in a city obsessed with digital gold.\n\nNow, at 30, Daniel is a cartographer of neighborhood lives. His 2.1-mile commute on the 38R Muni bus takes him to his station, where he begins his daily pilgrimage through the Haight and Cole Valley. He knows who\u2019s had a baby, who\u2019s moving out, and which elderly residents wait by the window for his arrival. He\u2019s a silent observer of the city\u2019s constant churn, a familiar face in a sea of strangers.\n\nHis social life is a small, tight-knit circle of high school friends who stayed in the Bay Area. His evenings are modest\u2014simple home-cooked meals, basketball games on TV, and his burgeoning passion for street photography, capturing the overlooked details of the city he sees every day. Daniel doesn't dream of a Silicon Valley fortune. His aspirations are grounded: save enough for a down payment on a small condo, maybe in Daly City, and one day take a trip to Korea to see the country his parents left behind. He finds a quiet dignity in his work, delivering connection in a city that can often feel disconnected, one letter at a time."
